ut things as petty as this, but it has to be said.<br>
<br>
When you sign up for a raid, scheduled at a time late on, with no loot is reserved, that's what you expect when you get there.  So, you've spent two hours beating giants and buffing up.  Fair enough, it's fine.  It's 3AM by this point, we charge the Lady ten minutes later.  She falls pretty quick (she did her good old fashioned 205 routine on me before she died, I lived this time, a first in a Vox raid).<br>
<br>
Yay!  Book drops!  It's about 3:30AM by now, and I'm really faltering.  It's getting even later for other people.<br>
<br>
We get to the rolls.  I have my /random button ready.  And then out of the blue, the /random ability disappears.  Why?  The friends of one paladin (Suometar in this case, no sense in not naming names) jump in, basically telling every other paladin not to roll or face the consequences.  With a heavy heart, we don't.  Three other 52 paladins sat there, probably half way between gobsmacked and happy for Suometar.  The looting goes on.<br>
<br>
This isn't a regular &quot;I L0st teh l000tz!!111!  F4g0tz, ur gh3y!!111!&quot; post.  I'm not calling anyone teh sukc or anything ridiculous like that.  Honest to god, I'm really happy Suometar got herself out of the 52 rut, because I know exactly how much it sucks (we were talking about it the other day, apparently, although neither of us were too close to how long Korhil waited, we were well on our way, and we'd both started around the same time).  However, on a no-claims raid, where the only drop you're interested in is for your epic, it's 3AM, you expect to get there, have it drop and at least have a chance to say to the planned receiver &quot;Here, honestly, you complete the epic, I'll wait longer.&quot;  It's NOT a decision that should be forced on people.<br>
<br>
There will be those who say &quot;Wanna complain about ph4t l00tz??  Go run your own $*%&amp;in' raid!!&quot;  I have tried, twice so far.  The planning stage took a day too long unfortunately (I make a point to have a core of 15 people ready to go, and pick it up from there) and twice the dragons were reserved, once by the Tribbles, the other by the Fellowship.  I'd run a raid if I ever though I had a chance of getting at the poor bastard of a dragon (hoping to this week).  I've also been told by several people to make the loot that I want reserved.  I can't do that.  Why?  It's crap.  You can't just reserve an epic drop on something like Vox or Naggy.  These guys are just about the only gankable dragons that most guilds have the power to do.  Everyone deserves a chance at their drop.  Everyone.<br>
<br>
I don't mind losing anything in a fair /random roll, heck, I'm happy for people.  Hell, I wouldn't have minded if the question had been put to the paladins present &quot;Guys, Suo's done a really good job here, will you give the book up for her?&quot;  The answer would have been yes, the paladins on the raid were some of the nicest I've known.  Forcing it was not the way to go.<br>
<br>
Scotty got the RBB two weeks back at Vox, I didn't get that.  I actually had to fight for him to get that (at the time, we had casters rolling for it, I had to point out repeatedly that it was simply a melee item, then search through the rolls to find the highest one, then point THAT out repeatedly).  He's been using it ever since, it's great for him.  I'm happy for Bromax, Korhil and everyone else who won a book over me in a dragon raid.  I'm happy for Suo, being finally able to complete Fiery Avenger.  I've told all of these people that if they want an extra hand for Miragul, they have it from me.  However, going on a raid where supposedly nothing is reserved, at 3AM, and then having it dropped on you that you're no longer allowed to roll on something you've been waiting for (in this case either the burnt or frost book) for something like 8-9 raids.  Even worse when the first person to /random gets a 319 and you think &quot;YES, I might stand a chance!&quot;<br>
<br>
That's all I really have to say.  I'm sorry if I offended anyone, and ironically, the raid leader had nothing to do with this ridiculous situation (she actually laid down the rules and was going to follow them until what I can only describe as a pressganging).  I'm very happy for Suometar and hope she'll let me kill Miragul with her.  No hard feelings to anyone, but it had to be said.  I've done too many dragon raids and lost out fairly too many times to honestly let this one fly. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bjond>Bjond</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1584<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(11/25/02 6:49:55 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> That's not good form at all</span><hr size=1> They really should stick to the declaration or they end up abusing people's trust and leading them on with false hopes for loot.  However, odd things can happen in these situations.  I recall one time where our raid leader asked us to come help him kill the Queen in Chardok for his epic.  He also invited a warrior friend of his, who (he said) wanted to see what the fight was like and how to do it.<br>
<br>
So, we kill her and suddenly, this other guy wants the drop and our raid leader says to let him take it.  Seems our leader had asked us to help him, but then had promised the first drop to his friend.  The friend got all kinds of nasty tells just like you did (ie. don't loot it or we'll all be very pissed off).  Not a good event.<br>
<br>
Could be something along those lines happened.  Guild all thinks it's for their Pally, but the raid leader promised open unbeknownst to them.  My one advice to you on this kind of topic is to never keep silent.  If you want it, go ahead and roll.  The long suffering act just gives the dynamite more time to breed up before the fuse gets there.  If they try to play games with you like they did, they're unlikely to help you in the future anyway and are probably not worth cultivating. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=valquisssilverpalm>Valquiss Silverpalm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 582<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(11/25/02 7:05:24 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: God this is strange...</span><hr size=1> I heard about this and I was both happy and a bit concerned.  A bit of back-story, since it's hit the boards.  This was a Fellowship raid, btw, and I'll take it upon myself as Saga's Ambassador to the Fellowship to answer for this early.<br>
<br>
Suometar has personally led at least 3 raids against Vox that I know of, possibly more.  She often has help, but she's always leading.  The raid after THREE books dropped, two of them won by non Fellowship attendees, concerned friends finally managed to force a reservation the next time, and of course that's the raid no book dropped.  This time Suometar did clearly post there were no reservations.  She's too damn honourable for her own good sometimes.<br>
<br>
The raid where three books dropped there was also a paladin who felt presured.  Again, no doing of Suometar's.  She almost had to force the book down his throat to make him take it, but she did.  She was also offered the only book won by a Fellowship member, of the three.  That was from Ninichka.  Again, she refused.<br>
<br>
I don't have the kind of explanation I might offer that would easily make sense to experience raiders, and I wasn't af Vox this time, but the truth of the matter is that the Fellowship are not experienced raiders.  We have the size and the force to do some impressive things, and we have been lately, but the Fellowship as a whole is stumbling though all the same old issues when it comes to fairness on raids.  We don't need to invite non-Fellowship members on a Vox raid, and certainly not the assortment of Paladins virtually certain to show up, but we tend to anyway.  Because no one has really confronted issues of fairness yet and how to deal with that on every level.<br>
<br>
So people are interjecting their own ideas of fair, which is both well-meant and potentially very explosive.  I always say post your rules and stick to them, to avoid confusion after the fact, and this is why.  But really that's a simplistic solution and only deals with problems, and not the core of the question.  How to be fair?<br>
<br>
I can tell you the Fellowship raids to have fun, not for loot.  I can tell you this is the first rumbling of dissatisfaction I've yet heard, and thank God it's mild.  And I can certainly tell you if casters were rolling on a Runed Bolster Belt it was by mistake.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
As a Fellowship raiding leader I'm dealing with this same problem now, and I've stuck my personal raids on a points system lately.  I don't know what's &quot;fair&quot; any more than the next leader, but I'm stumbling along trying to find it, anyway.<br>
<br>
I can also say that Suometar will probably be very distressed by this thread and will probably try to give her book away.  I don't know what will come of that and I won't presume to predict.  But I just want anyone who reads this thread to know that this isn't what the Fellowship is about.  We're just amatuer raiders, slightly distressed by the complications arising from our unexpected successes lately.<br>
<br>
Now, that all being said, I'd like to ask all Fellowship members who aren't ambassadors to refrain from posting here, so we can take our minor issue behind closed doors and deal with it in private.  If there are responses that need to be made here, Fellowship ambassadors will do it.<br>
<br>
Bakanome, your concerns will be addressed.  I'll be in touch.  I'm sure you realize you still have the option of expressing your concerns on this public board if you wish, but I hope you'll leave this alone unless and until you find private means aren't working.<br>
<br>
Valquiss<br>
